%I A382023 #66 Jul 21 2026 19:11:16
%S A382023 0,1,3,19,75,391,506163,13432040987
%N A382023 Number of distinct pairs-only half-sets in Q_n that form an equitable partition with their complements and are interchangeable with their complements under an automorphism of the hypercube graph.
%C A382023 Let Q(n) be the standard n-dimensional hypercube graph. Two vertices x and y in Q(n) are called "opposites" if they differ in every bit. A "pairs-only half-set" in Q(n) is a subset S of size 2^(n-1) such that, for every pair of opposite vertices, S contains either both vertices or neither. We count S and its complement as one object.
%C A382023 We say that S is "equitable" if all vertices in S have the same number of neighbors inside S, and all vertices in the complement of S have the same number of neighbors inside that complement.
%C A382023 Define a(n) as the number of pairs-only half-sets S, counted up to complementation, such that {S,S^c} is an equitable partition and some automorphism of Q(n) maps S onto S^c. Every automorphism of Q(n) is obtained by combining a permutation of the n coordinates with bitwise XOR by a fixed n-bit mask.
%C A382023 Identifying each pair of opposite vertices with a single vertex turns a pairs-only half-set into a 2-coloring of the antipodal quotient of Q(n), which is isomorphic to the folded cube FQ(n-1). Under this identification, the partition is equitable if and only if every quotient vertex has the same number k of oppositely colored neighbors. Thus the problem can be reformulated exactly in terms of such 2-colorings of FQ(n-1).
%C A382023 For n=7, the quotient is FQ(6), a 7-regular graph on 64 vertices. If f is the associated {+1,-1}-valued coloring vector and A is the adjacency matrix of FQ(6), then A*f = (7-2*k)*f. The nontrivial eigenvalues of FQ(6) are 3, -1, and -5. Hence the only possible values of k are 2, 4, and 6.
%C A382023 For n=7, the exact numbers of complement-pairs for k=2, 4, and 6 are respectively 441, 505715, and 7. Therefore a(7) = 441 + 505715 + 7 = 506163.
%C A382023 These three counts were independently verified by two different methods: direct constrained enumeration of the antipodal quotient and exact projected #SAT model counting.
%C A382023 The 1012326 oriented colorings for n=7 form 24 pairwise disjoint automorphism orbits: 2 for k=2, 21 for k=4, and 1 for k=6. A separate standalone verifier reconstructed Q(7) directly, generated all 645120 automorphisms of Q(7), found 322560 distinct induced actions on the antipodal pairs, independently recomputed the 24 orbit sizes, and exhibited and directly checked an automorphism mapping each orbit representative to its complement. Thus every one of the 506163 equitable complement-pairs satisfies the automorphism condition in the definition of a(7).
%C A382023 From _Constantinos Kourouzides_, Jul 16 2026: (Start)
%C A382023 More generally, for n >= 3, the folded-cube spectrum implies that the number k of oppositely colored neighbors in any such equitable coloring must be even.
%C A382023 For n=8, the antipodal quotient is FQ(7), an 8-regular graph on 128 vertices. The possible nonconstant values of k are therefore 2, 4, 6, and 8.
%C A382023 Write A_8(k) for the number of exact-k equitable complement-pairs that are interchangeable with their complements under an automorphism of Q(8). The independently certified small-case contributions are A_8(2) = 868, A_8(6) = 868, and A_8(8) = 1.
%C A382023 For k=4, the bipartition of FQ(7) gives an exact factorization: an oriented coloring is an ordered pair (u,v), where u and v are independently chosen from the set X of oriented n=7, k=4 colorings. Since |X| = 1011430, there are |X|^2 = 1022990644900 oriented equitable colorings, or 511495322450 complement-pairs, before imposing the automorphism condition.
%C A382023 A coupled orbit-stabilizer computation under the group induced by Aut(Q(8)) reduces the 1022990644900 oriented k=4 colorings to 408501 orbits under the bipartition-preserving subgroup. The total oriented weight of the complement-swappable orbits is 26864078500, giving A_8(4) = 26864078500/2 = 13432039250.
%C A382023 Therefore a(8) = A_8(2) + A_8(4) + A_8(6) + A_8(8) = 868 + 13432039250 + 868 + 1 = 13432040987.
%C A382023 The final k=4 classification was verified independently by a second program that did not reuse the producer's orbit-classification routine. It exhaustively searched the relevant stabilizer cosets for all 408501 orbit representatives, supplied an explicit automorphism witness for every positive class, and certified every negative class by exhaustion. (End)
%H A382023 Constantinos Kourouzides, <a href="/A382023/a382023_2.txt">C++ program</a>
%e A382023 The number of distinct, pairs-only half-sets in Q(3) with the desired properties is 3.
%e A382023 We label the vertices of the 3-dimensional hypercube Q(3) by these eight binary strings of length 3: 000, 001, 010, 011, 100, 101, 110, 111.
%e A382023 A half-set in Q(3) must contain a total of 4 vertices. We are interested in picking only opposite pairs of vertices. There are exactly three such half-sets that satisfy the following conditions: (1) each half-set and its complement form an "equitable" partition (every vertex in the set has the same number of neighbors in the set, and similarly for every vertex in the complement), (2) the induced subgraphs of the set and its complement are isomorphic, and (3) there is an automorphism of Q(3) that sends the set to its complement.
%e A382023 Those three half-sets are:
%e A382023   A = 000, 111, 101, 010
%e A382023   B = 100, 011, 101, 010
%e A382023   C = 000, 111, 100, 011
%e A382023 They satisfy the conditions because:
%e A382023 In cases A, B and C, the subgraphs induced by each of the sets form two disjoint edges, and the complement also forms two disjoint edges. This means every vertex in the set has exactly one neighbor in the set, and the same applies to the complement, so the partition is equitable. Both subgraphs are therefore isomorphic.
%e A382023 Each of these sets can be mapped to its complement by adding a particular binary vector of length 3 to all its elements. For instance, if we add the binary vector 001 to each vertex of set A, we obtain exactly A's complement. A similar approach works for B and C.
%K A382023 nonn,more,changed
